    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-04-24T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-04-24T20:00:00-05:00" n="322"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d322">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 FEAC (<gloss target="#t_Info1"
                        >Info</gloss>)/4–2447: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Political Adviser in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-04-24T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 24, 1947—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>144. <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> 16. <hi rend="italic">Advance Transfers
                        of Reparations</hi>. USSR rep at <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> meeting
                    Apr 17 continued attacks on Advance Transfers paper, this time on procedural
                    grounds, but received no support from other members of Commission. He also made
                    highly emotional statement to Commission, claiming USSR Govt deeply hurt
                    because, although USSR supported claims of France, India and Australia to share
                    of advance transfers, no one except himself even mentioned USSR as possible
                    recipient; also because rec’d no seconds to his proposed amendments. This new
                    Soviet line has Commission somewhat puzzled.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Removals of Industrial Facilities and Merchant Shipping</hi>.
                    Some members of Economics Committee claim cannot discuss U.S. proposal until are
                    furnished with paper explaining why U.S. has in some cases departed from
                    principles and standards previously agreed upon (for example, proposing
                    production in Japan of 25,000 tons of primary aluminum per annum, whereas
                    interim removals decision permits only working of secondary aluminum). Otherwise
                    no specific objections yet interposed.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Release of Unpublished Decisions</hi>. Commission Apr 17
                    decided release for publication all hitherto unpublished decisions of <gloss
                        target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> except <pb facs="0402" n="388" xml:id="pg_388"
                    /> Red Cross decision and Assured Production Capacity Levels decision. Latter
                    being held pending notification from <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss> that
                    plants have been designated for retention. Release of other decisions noon Apr
                    18.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
